      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why J-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>J is the second-highest-value tile in Scrabble at 8 points (tied with X, behind only Q and Z at 10). With just one J tile in the bag, it's a rare draw — but when it arrives, it immediately transforms your scoring potential. Even a simple three-letter J-word like JAW (13 pts) outscores most five-letter plays made with common tiles.</p>
      <p>The J+Z combination in words like JAZZILY (35 pts), JAZZY (33 pts), and JAZZED (32 pts) produces some of the highest base scores in the entire game. Landing these on premium squares can create 70-100+ point turns that swing entire games. Even without Z, J's 8-point base makes every J-word inherently valuable.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing J-Words</h2>
      <p>J is your highest-impact single tile. Here's how to maximize its value:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Always target premium squares:</strong> J is worth 8 points — on a double-letter square that's 16 points from one tile alone. On triple-letter, it's 24 points. Never play J on a plain square if a premium is accessible within one turn.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Know your short J-words:</strong> JO (9 pts), JAB (12 pts), JAW (13 pts), JAY (13 pts), JOY (13 pts) — these compact plays fit anywhere and score heavily. JO in particular is a lifesaver on tight boards.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't hold J too long:</strong> J has limited word options. If you're holding it for 2+ turns waiting for the perfect play, you're sacrificing flexibility on every other turn. A 13-point JAW now is often better than hoping for a 35-point JAZZILY that may never materialise.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>J without vowels — use FJORD:</strong> If your rack is consonant-heavy, remember FJORD doesn't need a vowel next to J. Also consider playing J in a separate short word while using remaining tiles for a parallel play.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Endgame J danger:</strong> Getting stuck with J at game end costs you 8 points (subtracted from your score). If the bag is nearly empty and you can't play J productively, dump it ASAP — even a JO for 9 points is better than -8 at endgame.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The J + Z Power Combo</h2>
      <p>If you ever hold both J and Z simultaneously, you're sitting on some of the most explosive scoring potential in Scrabble:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>JAZZILY (35 pts):</strong> The highest-scoring J-starter. If you have J+A+Z+Z+I+L+Y — play it immediately for the bingo bonus plus 35 base points (85 total!)</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>JAZZY (33 pts):</strong> Only 5 letters but 33 points. On a double-word square, that's 66 points from a compact play that leaves you 2 tiles for next draw.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>JINX (18 pts):</strong> Combines J and X — another premium pairing. Four letters, 18 points before any board multipliers.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Essential Two and Three-Letter J-Words</h2>
      <p>These are non-negotiable memory items for competitive Scrabble. The short J-words unlock scoring in tight board positions:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>JO (9 pts):</strong> The only valid two-letter J word. Worth memorising above all others — it fits anywhere and guarantees J doesn't get stuck on your rack.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Three-letter J gems:</strong> JAB (12), JAG (11), JAM (12), JAR (10), JAW (13), JAY (13), JIG (11), JOB (12), JOG (11), JOT (10), JOY (13), JUG (11), JUT (10)</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Average value:</strong> Three-letter J-words average 11.5 points — that's higher than most 5-6 letter words made with common tiles</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">J in the Endgame</h2>
      <p>J becomes dangerous in the endgame. Here's how to handle it:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Tile count awareness:</strong> Track the bag. When fewer than 10 tiles remain and you're holding J, prioritise playing it even if the scoring opportunity isn't optimal.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>JO is your safety valve:</strong> With only a vowel needed, JO can almost always be played somewhere. It's 9 points you gain versus 8 points you'd lose — a 17-point swing compared to getting stuck.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Opponent awareness:</strong> If your opponent is stuck with J in the endgame, you benefit from their -8 penalty. Consider blocking J-friendly positions near game end if you suspect they're holding it.</span></li>
      </ul>

